I think I&#x27;m actually in total disagreement with this. I think using semicolons as statement terminators is quite easy and doesn&#x27;t require any knowledge of the ASI in terms of _adding_ semicolons. The one (potential) issue with not being aware of the ASI when using semicolons as statement terminators is for something like:<p><pre><code>  return
    {
      a: 0
    };
</code></pre>
since you can&#x27;t disable ASI. Even in the above case, however, &quot;standard&quot; JS style would prevent the issue.

See the following example for why that is excluded.<p><pre><code>    public string Foo { get { return &quot;&quot;; } }

    private void DoBar(ref string input) { input = &quot;123&quot;; }

    public void Main() { DoBar(ref Foo); }
</code></pre>
Typically C# points you towards using a different methodology than ref/out parameters. But I do agree it is annoying when you want to use them.
